### 5 Nov 2013
# Implementing a Simple Drawing Language (Part 2)

In the first part of these series, I wrote about how the parser is organized. Now, I'm going to write about its commands - how we set them, what they are and how we execute them.

So, one of the task's requirements is that new language syntax should be easy to add. So, if we make a simple array of functions which execute these commands, all it would take to add a new functionality will be to add a function to that array. But a function is associated with a token, so we would make a map of key, value pairs.

```
// We'll use C++11's <functional> part of the standard library
std::vector<std::pair<char, std::function<void(int)>>> executionMap;
```

How we add a command? Let's make a function which does this for us:

```
void AddCommand(char token, std::function<void(int)> executionFunction)
{
    executionMap.push_back(std::make_pair(token, executionFunction));
}
```

And the calling of the command is just as simple. We take a pair of the token and parameters and based on them, we find the appropriate function and call it with the needed parameter.

```
void CallCommand(std::pair<char, int> command)
{
    for (auto execFunc = executionMap.begin(); execFunc != executionMap.end(); ++execFunc)
    {
        if (execFunc->first == command.first)
        {
            execFunc->second(command.second);
            return;
        }
    }

    // what happens if we haven't found the appropriate command?
}
```

But from where we get those commands? Do you remember the parser? There was a variable called `commandQueue`. In it we store the input commands. It's a queue of pairs - `std::queue<std::pair<char, int>>`. After we've reached the 'r' symbol, we call a function which traverses it and executes each command.

```
void ExecuteCommandQueue()
{
    while (!commandQueue.empty())
    {
        std::pair<char, int> currentCommand = commandQueue.front();
        commandQueue.pop();
        CallCommand(currentCommand);
    }
}
```

And here's how we can add each command:

```
void main()
{
    // Thanks to C++11 standard, we can use lambdas
    AddCommand('p', 
       [](int param)
    {
        std::printf("Selecting pen No: %i\n", param);
    });
}
```

In the next post we are going to put it all together!


