### 3 Nov 2013
# Implementing a Simple Drawing Language (Part 1)

If you've read [The Pragmatic Programmer](http://pragprog.com/the-pragmatic-programmer), you may have stumbled upon a task which asks you to write a parser for a simple drawing language. Its syntax would represent the following thing:

```
p 2 // Use the pen with index 2
d   // Put the pen down
n 2 // Draw 2 cm north
e 1 // Draw 1 cm east
w 4 // Draw 4 cm west
s 1 // Draw 1 cm south
u   // Put pen up
r   // Run plotter
```

So, let's implement it in C++.

First, we need some basic specifications. 

A pen will have an index and a character with which it will draw. A command will consist of a token and an optional parameter. There will be a plotter which will handle all the drawing and command execution. We'll handle errors by simply outputting a string to stdout. There'll be two types of errors - Logic and Syntax. The first will be errors like the user haven't selected a pen but wanting to draw. The latter would be simply errors of invalid tokens. With that said, we can begin reasoning about the design and code of our simple interpreter. 

Let's begin with the parsing. We'll need a way of detecting and interpreting the user's input. A simple implementation would be to create an infinite loop in which we'll read input and execute commands according to it.

```
while (true)
{
    std::string tokenLine;
    std::getline(std::cin, tokenLine);
    char cmd = tokenLine[0];
    tokenLine.erase(0, 2);

    if (cmd == 'r')
    {
        ExecuteCommands();
        return;
    }

    int arg;
    sscanf_s(tokenLine.c_str(), "%i", &arg);
    commandQueue.push(std::make_pair(cmd, arg));
}
```

There are couple of problems with this code. First, it relies on many assumptions. Like, we are sure that the user will insert the tokens as we have specified them - he won't type unnecessary whitespaces. Second, the `while (true)` condition isn't considered a good design practice. Why don't we just put that condition in the loop and prevent it from bloating the code logic? With that in mind, here's the refactored code.

```
void ParseInput()
{
    std::string tokenLine;
    std::getline(std::cin, tokenLine);
    // Reduce is a utility function which removes the unnecessary whitespaces in a string
    tokenLine = Reduce(tokenLine); 
    char cmd = tokenLine[0];
    tokenLine.erase(0, 2);

    while (cmd != 'r')
    {
        int arg;
        sscanf_s(tokenLine.c_str(), "%i", &arg); 
        commandQueue.push(std::make_pair(cmd, arg));

        std::getline(std::cin, tokenLine);
        tokenLine = Reduce(tokenLine); 
        char cmd = tokenLine[0];
        tokenLine.erase(0, 2);
    }

    ExecuteCommands();
}
```

That's better! But we have some code duplication! We can isolate the getting of the next command in a separate function.

```
char GetNextCommand(std::string &tokenLine)
{
    std::getline(std::cin, tokenLine);
    tokenLine = Reduce(tokenLine);
    char cmd = tokenLine[0];
    tokenLine.erase(0, 2);

    return cmd;
}
```

We can use that in ParseInput() now:

```
void ParseInput()
{
    std::string tokenLine;
    char cmd = GetNextCommand(tokenLine);

    while (cmd != 'r')
    {
        int arg;
        sscanf_s(tokenLine.c_str(), "%i", &arg);
        commandQueue.push(std::make_pair(cmd, arg));

        cmd = GetNextCommand(tokenLine);
    }

    ExecuteCommandQueue();
}
```

OK, we're done with the parser. In the next post I'm going to write about how we'll organize our commands.


